| **QA Testing (Tester)**                                                                                              | **Developer Testing (Developer)**                                                            |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Focuses on verifying that the entire application works correctly and is free from defects.                           | Focuses on identifying and fixing code-level issues as early as possible during development. |
| Testers evaluate the complete system through various functional and non-functional tests.                            | Developers test the code they write to ensure it behaves as expected.                        |
| Usually performed after the software or feature has been developed.                                                  | Performed before the code is committed or merged into the shared repository.                 |
| Involves collaboration among testers, developers, and business stakeholders.                                         | Often involves collaboration between developers through code reviews and peer testing.       |
| Ensures the product meets business requirements and user expectations.                                               | Ensures new code is stable and does not introduce obvious defects.                           |
| Includes different types of testing such as regression, usability, performance, security, and accessibility testing. | Primarily includes unit testing and basic integration testing.                               |
| Validates the overall quality and reliability of the application.                                                    | Validates the correctness and quality of individual code components.                         |


2.Unit Testing is mainly performed by developers.

A unit is the smallest testable part of an application, such as a function, method, or class. Developers write and execute unit tests to verify that each unit works correctly before integrating it with other parts of the system.

Example:
If a developer creates a function to calculate employee salary, they will write unit tests to check whether the function returns the correct salary for different inputs.
Unit testing is important because it:

Finds defects early in the development process.
Reduces debugging time and development costs.
Improves code quality and reliability.
Makes code easier to maintain and modify.
Prevents regression issues when new changes are introduced.
Increases developer confidence before code is integrated into the application.
Supports Continuous Integration (CI/CD) by automatically validating code changes.

Benefits:

Faster development cycles
Better software quality
Reduced maintenance effort
Easier refactoring

Quality Control (QC) is the process of identifying defects in a product and ensuring that it meets the specified quality requirements before delivery to customers.

In software development, QC focuses on testing and verification activities to detect bugs and issues in the application.
